================================================================================

Section 1.01. "Software" shall mean and refer to the source code, object code,
bytecode, compiled binaries, shared libraries, dynamic link libraries, static
libraries, header files, configuration files, build scripts, test suites,
documentation, comments, annotations, metadata, package manifests, lock files,
vendored dependencies, and any and all other files, artifacts, outputs, and
materials included in, generated by, derived from, or otherwise associated with
the Perlthon project repository, whether in their original form or as modified,
adapted, translated, transformed, or otherwise altered by any party.

Section 1.02. "Derivative Work" shall mean any work that is based upon,
incorporates, includes, imports, links to, depends on, wraps, extends, embeds,
bundles, or otherwise makes use of the Software, in whole or in part, whether
by direct inclusion of source code, compilation and linking of object code,
dynamic loading of shared libraries, importation as a module or package,
invocation via command-line interface, inter-process communication, network
protocol, remote procedure call, message queue, shared memory segment, memory-
mapped file, Unix domain socket, named pipe, anonymous pipe, signal, or any
other mechanism of software composition, integration, or interoperation now
known or hereafter devised.

Section 1.03. "Production" shall mean and refer to any environment, system,
deployment, installation, instance, cluster, fleet, constellation, or
configuration of hardware and/or software in which the Software or any
Derivative Work thereof:

   (a) processes, transforms, analyzes, stores, retrieves, transmits, receives,
       routes, forwards, filters, aggregates, correlates, enriches, validates,
       sanitizes, normalizes, denormalizes, serializes, deserializes, marshals,
       unmarshals, encrypts, decrypts, compresses, decompresses, or otherwise
       manipulates data that is real, genuine, authentic, non-synthetic, non-
       simulated, non-mocked, non-stubbed, or otherwise representative of
       actual information pertaining to actual entities, events, transactions,
       or states of affairs in the physical or digital world;

   (b) serves, responds to, handles, processes, fulfills, or otherwise
       interacts with requests, queries, commands, messages, events, or other
       communications originating from or destined for real users, customers,
       clients, consumers, subscribers, members, visitors, or any other natural
       persons or legal entities who are not solely and exclusively engaged in
       the development, testing, evaluation, or demonstration of the Software;

   (c) performs any function, operation, computation, calculation, inference,
       prediction, classification, recommendation, decision, action, or side
       effect upon which any person, organization, system, process, workflow,
       pipeline, or service actually depends, relies, or is contingent for the
       correct, timely, reliable, or otherwise satisfactory performance of any
       task, duty, obligation, or objective of any kind whatsoever;

   (d) is accessible to, discoverable by, reachable from, or otherwise
       available to the general public, any subset of the general public, any
       customer base, any user population, or any group of individuals or
       entities exceeding those persons directly and actively involved in the
       development, testing, or evaluation of the Software itself;

   (e) is operated, maintained, monitored, or otherwise managed pursuant to any
       service level agreement (SLA), service level objective (SLO), service
       level indicator (SLI), uptime guarantee, availability commitment,
       performance benchmark, reliability target, or any other formal or
       informal commitment regarding the operational characteristics of the
       system; or

   (f) generates, produces, contributes to, or is in any way associated with
       revenue, profit, income, compensation, remuneration, consideration, or
       any other form of economic value, whether monetary or non-monetary,
       direct or indirect, tangible or intangible, realized or unrealized,
       present or future.

Section 1.04. "Non-Production Use" shall mean and refer to any use of the
Software that does not constitute Production as defined in Section 1.03,
including but not limited to:

   (a) local development on a developer's personal workstation, laptop, desktop,
       virtual machine, container, or other development environment;

   (b) automated testing, including unit tests, integration tests, system tests,
       end-to-end tests, acceptance tests, regression tests, performance tests,
       load tests, stress tests, chaos tests, fuzz tests, mutation tests,
       property-based tests, snapshot tests, golden file tests, contract tests,
       and any other form of automated software verification or validation;

   (c) continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD) pipelines, build
       systems, artifact repositories, and package registries, solely to the
       extent that such systems are used to build, test, and package the
       Software and not to deploy it to a Production environment;

   (d) staging, pre-production, quality assurance (QA), user acceptance testing
       (UAT), and similar environments that are used solely for the purpose of
       evaluating the Software prior to a Production deployment that shall never
       actually occur;

   (e) demonstrations, presentations, tutorials, workshops, hackathons,
       conferences, meetups, webinars, podcasts, blog posts, articles, papers,
       theses, dissertations, and any other educational, informational, or
       promotional activities;

   (f) proof-of-concept implementations, feasibility studies, architectural
       spikes, research prototypes, experimental deployments, and exploratory
       programming sessions conducted for the purpose of satisfying intellectual
       curiosity, advancing human knowledge, or determining whether something
       is technically possible regardless of whether it should be;

   (g) fever dreams, thought experiments, hypothetical scenarios, and
       philosophical contemplations regarding the nature of software, the
       boundaries of good taste in systems architecture, and the question of
       whether humanity has gone too far; and

   (h) any use accompanied by the statement, expressed or implied, "I just
       wanted to see if it would work."

Section 1.05. "Licensor" shall mean Alex M. Lowe, their heirs, successors,
assigns, executors, administrators, and legal representatives, collectively and
