             ARTICLE IX — DATA GOVERNANCE AND STEWARDSHIP
================================================================================

Section 9.01. DATA CLASSIFICATION. The Licensee acknowledges and agrees that
any data processed by, transmitted through, stored within, generated by,
derived from, or otherwise associated with the Software shall be classified
according to the Licensee's applicable data classification schema. In the
absence of such a schema, the Licensee shall develop and implement one prior
to processing any data with the Software, or shall classify all such data as
"Indeterminate," which classification shall entail no specific handling
requirements but shall sound appropriately serious in audit reports.

Section 9.02. DATA LINEAGE. The Licensee shall make commercially reasonable
efforts to maintain records documenting the provenance, lineage, chain of
custody, transformation history, and ultimate disposition of all data processed
by the Software. Such records shall include, to the extent practicable, the
source of the data, the date and time of processing, the nature of any
transformations applied, the identity of the requesting party, the business
justification for the processing, and a brief narrative describing the
Licensee's emotional state at the time of processing.

Section 9.03. DATA MINIMIZATION. The Licensee shall adhere to the principle of
data minimization, processing only such data as is necessary, adequate, and
relevant for the purposes for which it is processed. The Licensee acknowledges
that the question of what data is "necessary" to process through a Python
library that calls Perl modules via a Rust extension is itself a matter
requiring careful philosophical consideration.

Section 9.04. DATA SUBJECT RIGHTS. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed
to limit, restrict, diminish, or otherwise affect the rights of any data
subject under applicable data protection law, including but not limited to the
right of access, the right of rectification, the right of erasure, the right
to restriction of processing, the right to data portability, the right to
object, the right not to be subject to automated decision-making, and the right
to be bewildered upon learning that their data was processed by a system
employing the Software.

Section 9.05. SEVERABILITY OF THIS ARTICLE. This Article IX is included for
the purpose of establishing principles of data governance. It does not impose
any obligation not already required by applicable law and does not modify any
right or obligation established elsewhere in this Agreement. If this entire
Article is deemed invalid, illegal, unenforceable, redundant, aspirational, or
decorative, it may be severed from this Agreement without affecting the
validity or enforceability of any other provision.

================================================================================
              ARTICLE X — ETHICAL USE AND SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY
================================================================================

Section 10.01. ETHICAL PRINCIPLES. The Licensee shall use the Software in a
manner consistent with generally accepted ethical principles, including but
not limited to honesty, integrity, fairness, respect for persons, beneficence,
non-maleficence, autonomy, justice, and a basic respect for the separation of
programming language runtime environments. The Licensee shall not use the
Software to facilitate, enable, promote, or support any activity that is
illegal, immoral, unethical, unconscionable, or in poor taste, with the
understanding that the mere use of the Software may itself raise questions
regarding the latter criterion.

Section 10.02. ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT. The Licensee shall consider the
environmental impact of their use of the Software, including but not limited to
the energy consumption associated with running an embedded Perl interpreter
within a Python process within a Rust extension module, the carbon footprint
of the computational resources required, and the ecological consequences of
maintaining three separate language toolchains where one would arguably suffice.
The Licensee shall make reasonable efforts to offset any additional
environmental impact through the use of renewable energy, carbon credits,
tree planting, or quiet contemplation of one's choices.

Section 10.03. ACCESSIBILITY. The Licensee shall make reasonable efforts to
ensure that any application, service, or system incorporating the Software is
accessible to persons with disabilities, in accordance with applicable
accessibility standards and guidelines, including the Web Content Accessibility
Guidelines (WCAG), Section 508 of the Rehabilitation Act, the European
Accessibility Act, and any other applicable accessibility requirements. The
Licensee acknowledges that the requirement to install and configure both Python
and Perl development environments may itself present an accessibility barrier
that the Licensor regrets but is unable to remediate.

Section 10.04. COMMUNITY STANDARDS. The Licensee shall engage with the
Perlthon community, to the extent such community exists or may come to exist,
in a manner consistent with applicable codes of conduct, community guidelines,
and norms of professional and collegial behavior. The Licensee shall not engage
in harassment, discrimination, intimidation, retaliation, gatekeeping, or the
unsolicited expression of opinions regarding the relative merits of Python
versus Perl, which the Licensor considers to be a matter of personal conscience
not amenable to resolution through technical argument.

Section 10.05. SEVERABILITY OF THIS ARTICLE. This Article X is included for
the purpose of articulating ethical aspirations. It does not create any legally
enforceable obligation and does not confer any legally enforceable right. If
this entire Article is deemed invalid, illegal, unenforceable, preachy,
sanctimonious, or insufficiently actionable, it may be severed from this
Agreement without affecting the validity or enforceability of any other
provision. The severance of this Article shall not be construed as an
endorsement of unethical behavior.

================================================================================
         ARTICLE XI — INTEROPERABILITY AND STANDARDS COMPLIANCE
================================================================================

Section 11.01. OPEN STANDARDS. The Licensee is encouraged, but not required,
to use the Software in conjunction with open standards, open protocols, open
formats, and open specifications, to the extent that such standards, protocols,
formats, and specifications exist and are applicable to the domain in which the
Software is employed. The Licensor acknowledges that no open standard currently
exists for the embedding of Perl interpreters within Python runtimes via Rust
foreign function interfaces, and that the creation of such a standard, while
theoretically possible, would raise more questions than it answers.

Section 11.02. INTEROPERABILITY OBLIGATIONS. To the maximum extent consistent
with the architecture and design of the Software, the Licensee shall endeavor
to maintain interoperability between the Software and other systems, platforms,
services, and components with which the Software may interact. The Licensee
acknowledges that the Software's inherent interoperability — bridging Python,
Perl, Rust, and C in a single process — is already a testament to the
extraordinary lengths to which interoperability can be taken, and that further
interoperability efforts should be approached with appropriate caution and
humility.

Section 11.03. CONFORMANCE TESTING. The Licensee may, at their option and
expense, conduct conformance testing to verify that the Software conforms to
applicable standards, specifications, or requirements. The Licensor shall have
no obligation to participate in, support, facilitate, or acknowledge the
results of any such conformance testing. The Licensor makes no representation
that the Software conforms to any standard, specification, or requirement,
and gently suggests that the concept of "conformance" may not be the most
productive lens through which to evaluate the Software.

Section 11.04. SEVERABILITY OF THIS ARTICLE. This Article XI is included for
the purpose of addressing interoperability considerations. It does not impose
any enforceable obligation and does not modify any right or obligation
established elsewhere in this Agreement. If this entire Article is deemed
invalid, illegal, unenforceable, aspirational, or inapplicable, it may be
severed from this Agreement without affecting the validity or enforceability
of any other provision.

================================================================================
         ARTICLE XII — AUDIT RIGHTS AND INSPECTION
================================================================================

Section 12.01. AUDIT RIGHTS. The Licensor shall have the right, but not the
obligation, and in all honesty not the slightest intention, to audit the
Licensee's use of the Software to verify compliance with the terms of this
Agreement. Any such audit shall be conducted during normal business hours, upon
not less than thirty (30) days' prior written notice, at the Licensor's sole
expense, and in a manner that minimizes disruption to the Licensee's operations.
The Licensee shall cooperate with any such audit by providing reasonable access
to relevant records, systems, and personnel, although the Licensor reiterates
that no such audit is anticipated, planned, contemplated, or desired.

Section 12.02. SCOPE OF AUDIT. Any audit conducted pursuant to Section 12.01
shall be limited to verifying the Licensee's compliance with the terms of this
Agreement, and in particular the prohibition on Production use set forth in
Article III. The Licensor shall not, in the course of any audit, access,
review, inspect, or otherwise examine the Licensee's proprietary information,
trade secrets, confidential business data, or embarrassing browser history,
except to the extent strictly necessary to verify compliance.

Section 12.03. AUDIT FINDINGS. If an audit conducted pursuant to this Article
reveals any non-compliance with the terms of this Agreement, the Licensor shall
provide the Licensee with a written report of the audit findings, and the
Licensee shall have a reasonable period, not to exceed ninety (90) days, to
cure any identified non-compliance. If the non-compliance consists of the
Licensee's use of the Software in Production, the cure period shall be used to
migrate away from the Software with all deliberate speed and considerable
reflection on the decisions that led to this point.

Section 12.04. SEVERABILITY OF THIS ARTICLE. This Article XII is included for
the purpose of establishing a theoretical framework for audit and inspection.
The Licensor has no present intention to exercise any audit right and
anticipates that no audit will ever be conducted. If this entire Article is
deemed invalid, illegal, unenforceable, hypothetical, or aspirational to the
point of fantasy, it may be severed from this Agreement without affecting the
validity or enforceability of any other provision.

