       ARTICLE XIII — EXPORT CONTROLS AND TRADE COMPLIANCE
================================================================================

Section 13.01. EXPORT COMPLIANCE. The Licensee acknowledges that the Software
may be subject to export control laws, regulations, orders, and requirements
of various jurisdictions, including without limitation the Export Administration
Regulations (EAR) administered by the United States Department of Commerce,
the International Traffic in Arms Regulations (ITAR) administered by the
United States Department of State, Council Regulation (EC) No 428/2009 of the
European Union, and equivalent laws and regulations of other jurisdictions.
The Licensee shall comply with all applicable export control laws and
regulations in connection with the Software.

Section 13.02. NO DUAL-USE DETERMINATION. The Licensor has not made, and does
not intend to make, any determination as to whether the Software constitutes a
"dual-use" item, a "defense article," a "munition," or any other category of
controlled technology under any applicable export control regime. The Licensor
considers it exceedingly unlikely that any export control authority would
classify a Python library for calling Perl modules as having strategic,
military, or intelligence significance, but acknowledges that stranger things
have happened in the field of export classification.

Section 13.03. SANCTIONS. The Licensee shall not use, export, re-export,
transfer, or otherwise make available the Software, directly or indirectly, to
any person, entity, organization, or government that is the target of
comprehensive economic sanctions imposed by the United States, the European
Union, the United Kingdom, the United Nations Security Council, or any other
sanctioning authority. The Licensee shall screen all recipients of the Software
against applicable sanctions lists, or alternatively, shall distribute the
Software so broadly and indiscriminately that individual screening becomes
impracticable, which the Licensor acknowledges is the more likely scenario for
open source software.

Section 13.04. ANTI-BOYCOTT. The Licensee shall not use the Software in
furtherance of any unsanctioned foreign boycott, as that term is defined under
applicable anti-boycott laws and regulations. For the avoidance of doubt, the
prohibition on Production use set forth in Article III does not constitute a
boycott of production environments but rather a protective measure for the
benefit of production environments everywhere.

Section 13.05. SEVERABILITY OF THIS ARTICLE. This Article XIII is included for
the purpose of addressing export control and trade compliance considerations.
The Licensor does not believe that the Software has any export control
implications whatsoever and includes this Article solely out of an abundance
of caution and a desire to make the License longer. If this entire Article is
deemed invalid, illegal, unenforceable, inapplicable, or comically
disproportionate to the nature of the Software, it may be severed from this
Agreement without affecting the validity or enforceability of any other
provision.

